segments.text: during the election which in hindsight you think was unkind or anything like that?
No, we were pretty good friends and we didn't, we didn't, if it was I didn't, if it was Roger got away with it because I didn't find out about it.
So you won and what was the margin or do you remember?
I think it was
55-60%, something like that.
Did Dean Hannigan or anyone else call you in and give you any guidance or direction or?
Afterward?
Mm-hmm.
Uh-uh.
All right, what did you think your role was as president of the student body?
Well, I looked at it kind of from, we looked at it a little bit from a point of view of trying to get people to
think that it meant something instead of just holding office and voting on a new constitution or whatever.
And so that's when we decided to do the refrigerator deal.
We knew that a lot of students couldn't afford to pay $300 for a little refrigerator in their dorm.
And we didn't have permission from the administration to put the refrigerators in the dorm because of the electricity they would use anyway.
But we found this company that sold refrigerators

and they didn't want to sell them for 10 or 15 bucks a month payment but they said if we can do two or three thousand of them we can do them for 10 or 15 bucks a month and then take them back at the end of the year and stuff like that so we went we got permission from dr williams to put the refrigerators in and use the extra juice and then we got brought the company in to
start selling them and we sold them, we leased them through the student government and so thousands of them, I mean almost every dorm room eventually wound up having one.

It turned into the huge cash flow deal for for student government even to the point where we wouldn't have needed any money from the university or MSC to to finance operations and then that's when we moved started working on the
two other things.
We started working on the buses which eventually like six months afterwards came into being and we started working on a student credit union.
We wanted to bring a student credit union in and the banks locally just went crazy.
I mean they just screamed and hollered and started putting students on their boards, all those kinds of stuff to
offset that.
I think eventually a credit union came in, but it was pretty seriously opposed by financial institutions around College Station and Bryan when we were trying to bring a student credit union in.
Did you have any dreams, plans that obviously in hindsight weren't any good?
That weren't any good?
I'm sure I forgot.
I'm sure I did, but I worked hard to forget them.
Who did you turn to for advice?
Probably just a little cabinet I had.
There was a guy named Randy Ross, and there was a guy named Mike Esmeyer, who was really a hard worker.
He's the one that did the refrigerators.
And I lived with the Corps staff and the Corps commander and all those folks.
So the closest people to me were my fellow members of Corps staff.
Was there a kind of an unofficial campus student inner circle?
Yeah.
Who were they?
What were they?
Well, it was, it was, it was core staff, the head of civilian student council,
the cabinet of student government and Kirk Hawkins and the folks at the MSC.
They kind of got together pretty regularly to do stuff.
And did y'all ever go as a group to present any master plan of any sort to Dr. Williams?
Yeah, we wanted to do a, we revised the student constitution to allow more civilian input.
We thought that
And the Corps was not real crazy about that.
But it turned out good, because if we had kept it like it was, it was almost impossible to ever get any serious number of civilians into student government.
It's probably like a little Nixon gone to China deal.
Somebody in the Corps could do that, but Capernaum couldn't, or somebody like that.
And so we devised a new constitution that allowed

allowed people within student government to be elected from dormitories instead of popular vote just you know because we could one area could could block work the whole thing and I think that wound up helping because it got everybody involved in stuff at school.
What in hindsight what did you learn from that year that would be important to you in your public leadership years after that?
I guess, you know, I thought back to that time a lot.
I got a real charge out of doing stuff.

I mean, the refrigerator sounded like, you know, not a very big deal, but to a lot of students, that is a big deal, because they no longer had to walk all the way to Northgate or somewhere to get food that night if they wanted to eat in the dorm.
They could have something right there, and they never had that before, and that, I remember
We get calls, we get letters from people saying, hey, that was a neat deal and stuff like that.
And I like that feeling.
I like that part of it.
I think it did a lot to make me think public service might be something I want to get into.
All right.
Did you learn some negative things, some things not to try, not to do in later life?
Yeah, I'm sure.
But I can't think of them at the time.
You don't remember?
Yeah, don't talk to the press.
Hayden Whitsitt.
I remember the editor of the battalion was, we were all very wary of him and that's a feeling that hasn't left me.
Dealing with the press.
When you were getting ready to leave the campus as an Aggie graduate, how well prepared did you think A&M had made you?
Oh, I think good.
But as good as the academic part of it was, I have always believed that from what I have done in life, the outside of academic stuff was at least as important.
The student government service, the core, and things like that were

I mean, I think you have an opportunity at A&M, even if you're not in the Corps because of the opportunities the MSC avails you, that you have an opportunity to get two degrees, every kid does, one in academics and one in leadership, and the second one's free if you choose it.
What is it, maybe this is repetitive, what has it meant to you that you are an Aggie?
Well, it's meant an awful lot.
I mean, I think if, God, I try to think of what would happen if I had not gone to A&M and had gone to some other college.

I just get the impression that in most instances, some other college gives you a degree, a few people that you've known, and that's a wonderful deal, and I'm sure you'll make a great accountant and go down the road.
What I got here was just as good or better, probably a better degree, particularly as A&M's stature has grown.
I mean, it's kind of like the stock market.
Every year A&M gets better and better nationally, and my degree is worth more and more.
But aside from that, I think I've got a little share of stock in an entire network of people.
If I need to go, if I need to talk about
It's an accounting firm that I own part of now.

If I need to talk to somebody in Frito-Lay about tax policy or accounting or something like that, I'll find somebody in there that's got dash 73 or something by their name in the directory, and that's who I go to and say, who's the head duck and tell me how to get there.
And nine times out of ten, they can tell me how to get there or they are the head duck.
Let's make believe that you were hired now as a consultant to the Texas A&M leadership today.
That I was what?
That you're hiring out as a consultant?
Yeah.
What advice would you give them about Texas A&M right now?
To do or not do?
I would tell them
that you are under utilizing your assets and getting money out of the state and federal government for this institution.
That's what I tell them.
I tell them you're sitting there with 254 county agents.
You're sitting there with God knows how many captains or vice captains of industry all over the place.
All of which tomorrow
would call a legislator and say, let me talk to you about scholarship program at A&M, or let me talk to you about this line item, and all those kinds of things.
I mean, you could, you could bury them in, in goodwill, and we have never done that.
What else?
Anything you'd advise them to change or never change?
Well, I'll tell you what, they've done a lot better in the, in the spirit category than I thought was going to happen
in 1972 when I saw it in the rear view mirror that day.
And so I sure wouldn't change that.
I think they're doing a good job in recruiting kids and every kid I know wants to come here except mine.
Let's make believe that someone walked up to you and handed you a check for a million dollars with one restriction on it.
You must pass it on to Texas A&M
But you can decide to use to be made of that money.
If you could make a major gift to A&M, what would it be for?
Core.
To do what?
Recruitment.
To use for core scholarships and recruitment.
To pay for tutors and stuff like that.
To convince mom and dad.
Their tutoring program is starting good.
But to convince mom and dad that if you go there, you're going to get a... We've got enough money here to pay for
the very best tutors that are going to come in to these kids and do it.
Because that's the biggest concern of mom and dad when they get into the Corps.
Not that I think the Corps can ever be or should ever be the majority population of the campus, but I don't ever want it to go away.
I want there always to be a significant presence there.
And I think if kids that are coming here that may want to get in the Corps, that there are a lot of parents that are going,
You know, they remember back to my days or before me, and that's the place where they don't let you study.
You ought not do it.
And I'd put the money into making sure they had the best academic tutors they could get.
Allay the fears of mom and daddy.
What have we left out?
What topics have we not touched on that we should have?
Well, I don't know.
I can't imagine anything we missed.
All right.
I've got then one last question.
What feelings do you hold in your heart for Texas A&M today?
Nothing but good.
I do wish I could get the students to vote for one Democrat every now and then.
But I have nothing but warm feelings.
I believe that whatever little I have accomplished
I would have done none of it had I not had the experience at A&M.
I believe that.
I don't think, I don't think, I think if I had never gone to A&M, I would never have been a railroad commissioner, a comptroller of public accounts, a state senator, or a state representative.
I don't believe that would happen.
Not just because it wound up helping me get elected, but because the experiences led me that way to begin with.
That's a good conclusion.
